                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d210">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/1788: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-15T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 15, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 16—7:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>538. Referring to Department’s telegram of December 13, 8 p.m., No. 387.<note
                        n="29" xml:id="d210fn29">The same, <hi rend="italic">mutatis mutandis</hi>,
                        as telegram No. 228 to the Minister in Guatemala, printed in <ref
                            target="frus1941v06#pg_56">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, p.
                            56</ref>.</note> In a preliminary informal conversation with the
                    Minister of Foreign Affairs this afternoon, he expressed his willingness to
                    conclude an agreement along the lines of the Department’s telegram. I am
                    [sending?] him a note<note n="30" xml:id="d210fn30">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> embodying the provisions of the
                    agreement tomorrow morning.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
